Caption: In this June 27, 1979 file photo, Ted Bundy smiles during the second day of jury selection for his murder trial in a Dade County courtroom in Miami, Fla. Bundy is being tried for the murders of two women in Tallahassee on Jan. 15, 1978.

In this 1977 file photo, serial killer Ted Bundy, center, is escorted out of court at the Pitkin County courthouse, Aspen. In 2017, the Glenwood Springs Post-Independent re-discovered the 40-year-old photo of Bundy, along with others, that had been locked in an old newsroom safe, which a local locksmith volunteered to open. The pictures show Bundy in custody in 1977, the year he escaped from local law enforcement twice while awaiting a murder trial.
Credit/Source: Ross Dolan/Glenwood Springs Post Independent via AP

Caption: In this April 13, 1978 file photo, mourners say goodbye to Kimberly Leach at the funeral for the 12-year-old girl in Lake City, Fla. She disappeared Feb. 9, 1978, and was sexually abused and killed by Ted Bundy. Her body was two months later.

This 1977 file photo shows the jail cell from which suspected serial killer Ted Bundy escaped on Dec. 30, 1977, in Glenwood Springs. Bundy piled books under the blankets of his cot to make it appear that he was sleeping, and then cut a hole in the ceiling and climbed to the crawlspace, becoming a fugitive for the second time.

In this Jan. 25, 1989 file photo, a toy bunny is hung in effigy by Jerry Jackson of Atlanta Ga., wearing a Ronald Reagan mask, as a crowd celebrates the execution of Ted Bundy at sunrise in Starke, Fla.

In this Monday, June 25, 1979 file photo, Ted Bundy presents a motion during his murder trial in Miami. He complained that he could not work on his defense in a 9- by 7-foot cell. Bundy is charged with clubbing two young women to death in a sorority house in Tallahassee. (AP Photo)

In this Jan. 24, 1989 file photo, Louise Bundy, mother of convicted murderer Ted Bundy, wipes away a tear in her dining room in Tacoma, Wash., as she tells her son, "You will always be my precious son." He was executed minutes later.
Credit/Source: Russ Carmack, The News Tribune via AP

Caption: In this June 1977 file photo, police officers inspect a vehicles at a roadblock near Glenwood Springs. Suspected serial killer Ted Bundy escaped from the Pitkin County Courthouse on June 7, 1977.
Credit/Source: Ross Dolan/Glenwood Springs Post-Independent via AP

Caption: In this July 6, 1979 file photo, Ted Bundy, right, confers with Margaret Good, a member of his defense team, during jury selection for Bundy's murder trial in Miami, Fla. Bundy is accused of murdering two Florida State University students.
This 1979 file photo shows Ted Bundy, convicted murderer, in a Miami courtroom. (AP Photo)

Statues of Chinese gods are washed in preparation for the Lunar New Year celebration at a temple on the outskirts of Jakarta, Indonesia, Wednesday, Jan. 30, 2019. People of Chinese descent in the world's most populous Muslim country were preparing to celebrate the Lunar New Year of the Pig on Feb. 5.

In this Friday, Feb. 1, 2019, photo, children play with live Teacup pigs ahead of the Lunar New Year celebrations in the Chinatown area of Manila, Philippines. This year is the Year of the Pig in the Chinese Lunar calendar, which is supposed to represent abundance, diligence and generosity.
Young dancers perform the Blossoming Flowers Chinese Folk Dance during the 2019 Colorado Chinese New Year Celebration at Citypoint Church in Denver. on Feb. 2, 2019.

Bronze pig statues for sale at Hang Luoc street Lunar New Year fair, a favorite shopping place for local people in the Old Quarter, on Feb. 2, 2019, in Hanoi, Vietnam. The Chinese Lunar New Year also known as the Spring Festival in China, is celebrated from the first day of the first month of the lunar year and ends with Lantern Festival on the fifteenth day. Objects with pig symbols are on high demand as 2019 is the year of the pig.

Friends4Dance dancers Shiyi Shen, from left, of Bloomfield neighborhood in Pittsburgh, Deliu Zhou of Gibsonia, Pa., Rose Chen of Monroeville, Pa., and Jingyi Li, of Shadyside neighborhood in Pittsburgh, put on makeup together as they prepare backstage for the Greater Pittsburgh Chinese New Year Gala at Marshall Middle School on Feb. 2, 2019, in Marshall, Pa.
Credit/Source: Stephanie Strasburg, Pittsburgh Post-Gazette via AP

Caption: In this Saturday, Feb. 2. 2019, photo, ethnic Chinese artists perform a lion dance to celebrate the upcoming Chinese New Year at a shopping mall on the outskirts of Jakarta, Indonesia.

Buddhist monks walk at the Lama temple ahead of the upcoming Lunar New Year in Beijing on Feb. 3, 2019. Millions of Chinese are making their way to their hometowns, in the world's largest annual human migration, to celebrate the Lunar New Year with family on February 5.

A Chinese couple embrace as they prepare to separate to visit family for the holiday at Beijing Railway Station on Feb. 3, 2019, in Beijing, China. Millions of Chinese will travel home to visit families during the Spring Festival holiday period that begins with the Lunar New Year on Feb. 5, 2019.

People crowd on the street as they scramble for Chinese sweetcakes during Grebeg Sudiro festival on Feb. 3, 2019, in Solo City, Central Java, Indonesia. Grebeg Sudiro festival is held as a prelude to the Chinese New Year. People bring offerings known as gunungan, including Chinese sweetcakes piled up into the shape of mountains, which are paraded in the streets followed by Chinese and Javanese performers.
Smoke from incense sticks rises into the air as crowds pray for good fortune at Longhua temple in Shanghai to mark the start of the Lunar New Year, just before midnight on Feb. 4, 2019.

						Tony Sanchez tries to relax as he sits on the couch at his home in Greeley.  Since being diagnosed with Alzheimer’s, he lives with added anxiety and stress about the disease and what it means for his own future — and his family’s.
Credit/Source: Helen H. Richardson, The Denver Post

Caption: Helen H. Richardson, The Denver PostLEFT: Tony Sanchez keeps two boxes of pills on the living room table so he won’t forget to take the medicine he needs to treat symptoms of Alzheimer’s. RIGHT: Tony Sanchez takes marijuana out of a jar at his home in Greeley. He feels smoking pot helps with the anxiety bought on by the disease.
Credit/Source: Helen H. Richardson, The Denver Post

Caption: Helen H. Richardson, The Denver PostTeddy Sanchez, second from right, puts her arm around her husband Tony before his granddaughter’s volleyball game at Greeley Central High School. Tony and his ex-wife, Josie, at left, both have Alzheimer’s disease. Since the diagnosis, crowds at events like these can make Tony anxious, and he’s not likely to stay long.
Credit/Source: Helen H. Richardson, The Denver Post

Caption: Helen H. Richardson, The Denver PostTony Sanchez drives his Volkswagen Bug with his dog Lucy, his constant companion, in the back seat as he heads out to take her for a walk in Greeley. Tony walks Lucy four to five times a day, believing exercise will help slow his Alzheimer’s symptoms.
Credit/Source: Helen H. Richardson, The Denver Post

Caption: Helen H. Richardson, The Denver PostTony Sanchez works out before dawn at a local gym. In his efforts to fend off the symptoms of Alzheimer’s, he tries to hit the gym five times a week.
Credit/Source: Helen H. Richardson, The Denver Post

Caption: Helen H. Richardson, The Denver PostTony Sanchez, left, helps his ex-wife Josie choose a rosary for her weekly prayer session at the Fairacres Manor nursing home, where she lives, in Greeley.  Tony and Josie are both in the early stages of Alzheimer’s disease.
Credit/Source: Helen H. Richardson, The Denver Post

Caption: Helen H. Richardson, The Denver PostTony Sanchez, left, greets his granddaughter Aubree Raimer before a volleyball match at Greeley Central High School. Because crowds make him anxious since his Alzheimer’s diagnosis, Tony doesn’t stay long.
Credit/Source: Helen H. Richardson, The Denver Post
